21/11/2006

Croatian Prime Minister Ivo Sanader met with his Macedonian counterpart, Nikola Gruevski, in Zagreb on Monday (November 20th). 
The two said they were expecting "good news" from the forthcoming NATO summit regarding their countries' aspirations to join the Alliance. 
The two prime ministers also discussed economic co-operation, particularly trade in agricultural products.
***
Greek Prime Minister Costas Karamanlis, on a three-day visit to the United Kingdom, met on Tuesday (November 21st) with British counterpart Tony Blair. 
Talks focused on EU enlargement issues, the situation in the Balkans and Turkish-EU ties.
***
European Commission Vice-President Franco Frattini expressed the EU's expectations for free, fair and transparent local elections in Albania, during a joint news conference with Prime Minister Sali Berisha in Tirana on Friday (November 17th).
***
NATO Secretary-General Jaap de Hoop Scheffer praised Romania on Thursday (November 16th) for setting a good example of NATO member state participation in peacekeeping operations. 
He met with President Traian Basescu, Foreign Minister Mihai-Razvan Ungureanu and Defence Minister Sorin Frunzaverde in Bucharest.
***
Former Foreign Minister Miodrag Vlahovic has been approved as the new Montenegrin ambassador to the United States, MINA reported on Tuesday (November 14th). 
He is expected to go to Washington early next month.
***
Bilateral co-operation and the fight against the Kurdistan Workers' Party dominated the agenda of talks Thursday (November 16th) between Iraqi Prime Minister Nouri al-Maliki and his Turkish counterpart Recep Tayyip Erdogan.
***
Albanian President Alfred Moisiu arrived for a two-day visit to Poland on November 14th. 
Moisiu met with counterpart Lech Kaczynski, who assured Moisiu of Polish support for Albania's Euro-Atlantic integration course. 
Kaczynski also said Poland would be one of the first countries to ratify the Stabilisation and Association Agreement between Albania and the EU.
***
Swedish Foreign Minister Carl Bildt paid visits to Belgrade and Zagreb on Wednesday (November 15th) as part of his Balkan tour. 
In Belgrade, he met with President Boris Tadic to discuss Serbia's hopes of resuming talks with the EU.
***
Romanian President Traian Basescu and Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi agreed on Wednesday (November 15th) in Tripoli to resume bilateral relations, especially economic co-operation.
(Various sources -- 14/11/06-21/11/06)
